      "content": "The moisture-wicking performance of natural silk versus polyester is a classic case of **hydrophilic vs. hydrophobic** chemistry, but the results are often counterintuitive because of how the fibers interact with water at the molecular level.\n\nFirst, let's look at the **hydrophilicity** (water-loving nature). Natural silk is a **hydrophilic** fiber. This means it has a high affinity for water molecules. When sweat (which is mostly water) hits a silk surface, the water molecules are attracted to the hydroxyl groups on the silk's fibroin chains. This attraction causes the water to spread out and form a thin film on the surface rather than being absorbed into the bulk of the fiber. This is why silk feels cool and clammy to the touch; it actively pulls moisture away from the skin surface.\n\nIn contrast, polyester is a **hydrophobic** fiber. It is essentially a \"water-fearing\" material. The long, straight chains of the polyester molecules repel water molecules. When sweat hits polyester, it does not spread out; instead, it beads up and rolls off the surface due to surface tension. This means polyester does not actively pull sweat away from the skin; rather",
